b'<p>Actually, the two first ideas pass the <strong>array by address</strong> and the third passes the array <strong>by reference</strong>. You can devise a little test to check this:</p>
<pre><code>void test1(int* a) {
    a[0] = 1;
}

void test2(int a[]) {
    a[1] = 2;
}

void test3(int *&amp;a) {
    a[2] = 3;
}

int main() {
    int *a = new int[3]();
    a[0] = 0;
    a[1] = 0;
    a[2] = 0;

    test1(a);
    test2(a);
    test3(a);

    cout &lt;&lt; a[0] &lt;&lt; endl;
    cout &lt;&lt; a[1] &lt;&lt; endl;
    cout &lt;&lt; a[2] &lt;&lt; endl;
}
</code></pre>
<p>The output of this test is</p>
<pre><code>1
2
3
</code></pre>
<p>If a parameter is passed <strong>by value</strong>, it cannot be modified inside a function because the modifications will stay in the scope of the function. In C++, an array cannot be passed by value, so if you want to mimic this behaviour, you have to pass a <code>const int*</code> or a <code>const int[]</code> as parameters. That way, even if the array is passed by reference, it wont be modified inside the function because of the <code>const</code> property.</p>
<p>To answer your question, the preferred way would be to use a <code>std::vector</code>, but if you absolutely want to use arrays, you should go for <code>int*</code>.</p>'
